===Noun===
{{en-noun|-|s}}

# The quality of being [[confident]], not [[afraid]] or easily [[intimidate]]d, but without being [[incautious]] or [[inconsiderate]].
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1860|author=[[w:Ralph Waldo Emerson|Ralph Waldo Emerson]]|title=The Conduct of Life|passage=A great part of '''courage''' is the courage of having done the thing before.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1813|title={{w|Pride and Prejudice}}|author={{w|Jane Austen}}| passage=There is a stubbornness about me that never can bear to be frightened at the will of others. My '''courage''' always rises at every attempt to intimidate me.}}
#: {{ux|en|It takes a lot of '''courage''' to be successful in business.}}
# The ability to [[overcome]] one's fear, [[do]] or [[live]] things which one finds [[frightening]].
#* {{rfdate|en}}, {{w|Aristotle}}, ''Rhetoric, 1.9.8''
#*: ...'''courage''' is the thing by which they are able to take useful actions while amidst hazards...
#: {{ux|en|He plucked up the '''courage''' to tell her how he felt.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|1893|{{w|Mark Twain}}|Pudd'nhead Wilson and those Extraordinary Twins| http://www.worldcat.org/title/puddnhead-wilson-and-those-extraordinary-twins/oclc/61589871| 115| '''Courage''' is resistance to fear, mastery of fear — not absence of fear.}}
# The ability to [[maintain]] one's [[will]] or [[intent]] despite either the experience of [[fear]], or the occurrence of [[adversity]], [[frustration]], [[defeat]] or [[reversal]].
#* {{RQ:Emerson Self-Reliance}}
#*: Whatever you do, you need '''courage'''. Whatever course you decide upon, there is always someone to tell you that you are wrong. There are always difficulties arising that tempt you to believe your critics are right. To map out a course of action and follow it to an end requires some of the same '''courage''' that a soldier needs. Peace has its victories, but it takes brave men and women to win them.
#* {{tea room sense|en}} {{rfdatek|en|Winston Churchill}}
#*: Success is not final, failure is not fatal: it is the '''courage''' to continue that counts.
#* '''1942''', {{w|C.S. Lewis}}, ''{{w|The Screwtape Letters}}''
#*: “'''Courage''' is not simply one of the virtues but the form of every virtue ''at the testing point'', which means at the point of highest reality.”
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1960 |title={{w|To Kill a Mockingbird}}|author={{w|Harper Lee}}| passage=I wanted you to see what real '''courage''' is, instead of getting the idea that courage is a man with a gun in his hand. It's when you know you're licked before you begin, but you begin anyway and see it through no matter what.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|year=1993|author=Stanley P. Cornils|title=The Mourning After: How to Manage Grief Wisely|passage='''Courage''' isn't having the strength to go on - it is going on when you don't have strength.}}
#* '''2008''', {{w|Maya Angelou}}, address for the 2008 Cornell University commencement
#*: '''Courage''' is the most important of all the virtues because without courage, you can't practice any other virtue ''consistently''.
#* {{quote-book|en|year=2008|author=Eric Roth|title=The Curious Case of Benjamin Button Screenplay|passage=I hope you live a life you’re proud of. If you find that you’re not, I hope you have the '''courage''' to start all over again.}}

